<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10097b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10097b">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10097b"> 97(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> poudre de succession</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Sous Louis XIV, un inconnu, voulant avertir le roi d&apos;un pr&eacute;tendu complot pour empoisonner la famille royale, jette un billet sans signature dans un confessionnal de l&apos;&eacute;glise des J&eacute;suites de la rue Saint- Antoine. De l&agrave;, grand &eacute;moi et intervention du lieutenant g&eacute;n&eacute;ral de la police; deux malheureux sont mis &agrave; la torture. On ne d&eacute;couvre rien, et les empoisonnements continuent leur cours. On va jusqu&apos;&agrave; dire que la terrible <mark>poudre de succession</mark> se vend et se distribue par la Poste. <font color="green">[In the reign of Louis XIV, an unknown man, wishing to warn the king of an alleged conspiracy to poison the royal family, threw an unsigned note into a confessional in the Jesuit church on the rue St Antoine. Thence came great emotion and the intervention of the lieutenant general of the police. Two unfortunates were tortured. Nothing was discovered and the poisonings continued their course. It was even claimed that the terrible &lsquo;powder of succession&rsquo; was sold and delivered by post.]</font> <small> Arthur de Rothschild, <a name="ARHD" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ARHD"><cite title="source">Histoire de la poste</cite></a> (1876) 203</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
